	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />There aren't going to be adapter boards with flash already soldered on.
<br />Now's the time to learn, I guess. It isn't even that hard-- put a smaller tip in your iron, put down a ton of solder flux, tape the chip down, go over it again with flux, clean your soldering iron tip, put a big droplet of solder on it, drag it across the pins, feed more solder as you're going across if it runs out.
<br />
<br />It will "magically" work for the most part, but use solder braid to get rid of the three or so bridges between pins that do develop.
<br />
<br />No pinouts match the mask chips perfectly, hence the need for an adapter board.
<br />
<br />Anything that is 5 volts with enough address lines and an 8-bit data bus will work.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


